## Why Documents Matter More Than I Expected

I will be honest — when I saw today's topic I initially thought it would be one of the drier days in this challenge. Policies, standards, procedures — it sounds like paperwork. But the more I worked through it, the more I realized this is actually one of the most practical topics so far. Because without a clear document hierarchy, all the frameworks and risk assessments and compliance requirements I have been learning about have nowhere to land. They need to be captured in writing, in the right format, at the right level — or they simply do not get implemented consistently.

Today was about understanding how that structure works and why each layer exists.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Governance in cybersecurity is built on a layered document structure. The three levels are **Policy**, **Standard**, and **Procedure** — and each one serves a distinct purpose. Mixing them up, or skipping a level, leads to confusion, inconsistent implementation, and accountability gaps.

Here is how I am understanding each level:

**Policy** is the highest level. It expresses the intent and direction of leadership — what the organization has decided must be true, and why. A policy does not tell you how to do something. It tells you what is required and what values or obligations are driving that requirement. Policies are approved by senior leadership and apply across the organization.

**Standards** sit one level below policy. They take the intent expressed in a policy and translate it into specific, measurable requirements. Where a policy says "only authorized users may access patient data," a standard says "all user accounts must be protected with strong passwords of at least 12 characters and multi-factor authentication." Standards are testable and auditable — you can look at a system and determine whether it meets them or not.

**Procedures** are the most detailed level. They provide step-by-step instructions for carrying out the requirements defined in standards. A procedure does not set the rules — it explains exactly how to follow them. Procedures are written for the people doing the work: IT staff configuring systems, clinicians handling patient data, administrators managing access.

The relationship between the three levels is what makes the hierarchy powerful. A policy without supporting standards is just an aspiration. A standard without procedures is a requirement that nobody knows how to meet. And procedures without policies have no organizational authority behind them. All three levels need each other.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most for me today is the discipline required at each level — specifically the discipline to stay at the right level and resist the urge to drift.

When writing a policy, the temptation is to start explaining how things should be done. But a policy that gets into implementation details becomes outdated quickly, because technology and processes change faster than organizational intent does. A well-written policy should still be relevant five years from now even if the specific tools and systems have changed completely.

When writing a standard, the temptation is to either be too vague — sliding back toward policy language — or too specific — sliding down into procedure territory. The sweet spot is a measurable requirement: specific enough to test and audit, but not so detailed that it needs to change every time a system is updated.

When writing a procedure, the temptation is to leave things at a high level because the details feel tedious. But a procedure that is too vague defeats its own purpose. The whole point is that someone who has never done this task before can follow the procedure and do it correctly.

I found myself thinking about how often I have seen confusion in workplaces that came down to this exact problem — someone thought they were following the policy, but the standard said something more specific, and there was no procedure explaining how to actually do it. That kind of gap is where things fall through.

