## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2013 Advocate Medical Group data breach** in Illinois — one of the largest HIPAA breaches of that year, affecting nearly four million patients. Unencrypted laptops containing patient data were stolen from an administrative office.

When investigators examined what went wrong, part of the picture was a governance documentation failure. Advocate had a policy requiring encryption of devices containing patient data — but the standards and procedures needed to actually implement that policy consistently across the organization had not been fully developed or enforced. The policy said encryption was required. But without clear standards specifying which devices were in scope and procedures explaining how encryption was to be configured and verified, the policy did not translate into consistent action.

Advocate paid a settlement of $5.55 million to HHS — at the time the largest HIPAA settlement ever reached. The breach itself was a physical security failure. But the governance documentation failure is what allowed it to persist undetected and uncorrected.

That example made the document hierarchy feel very concrete. A policy is not a control. It is the starting point for a chain of documents that eventually produces a control. If any link in that chain is missing or weak, the intent of the policy does not reach the people who need to act on it.

